### 7. Sensitive Apache Configuration Files Exposed

**Affected Component:** Apache Authentication - `.htpasswd`, `.hta` files  
**CVSS v3.1 Score:** 7.4 (High)  
**CVSS Vector:** CVSS:3.1/AV:N/AC:L/PR:N/UI:N/S:U/C:H/I:L/A:N

#### Technical Description
Apache authentication files (`.htpasswd`) and configuration files (`.hta`) are accessible, exposing password hashes and access control configurations.

#### Evidence
```
Tool: ffuf
Paths: /.htpasswd, /.hta
Response: HTTP 200 OK
```

#### Impact Analysis
- **Password Hash Exposure:** `.htpasswd` contains bcrypt/MD5 hashed passwords
- **Offline Cracking:** Attackers can crack hashes offline
- **Configuration Disclosure:** `.hta` files reveal access control logic
- **Authentication Bypass:** Understanding auth logic aids bypass attempts

#### Detailed Remediation Steps

**Immediate Actions:**
```apache
# Apache - Block sensitive files
<FilesMatch "^\.ht">
    Require all denied
</FilesMatch>

# More comprehensive
<FilesMatch "^\.">
    Require all denied
</FilesMatch>
```

```nginx
# Nginx - Block hidden files
location ~ /\. {
    deny all;
    return 404;
}
```

**Password Rotation:**
```bash
# Regenerate .htpasswd with stronger hashing
htpasswd -cB /etc/apache2/.htpasswd username
# -B uses bcrypt (recommended)

# Move outside web root
mv /var/www/html/.htpasswd /etc/apache2/.htpasswd

# Update Apache config
AuthUserFile /etc/apache2/.htpasswd
```

**Verification:**
```bash
curl -I https://dvwa.csalab.app/.htpasswd
# Expected: HTTP 403 or 404
```

